#X text 24 82 The [mtof] object converts a MIDI pitch value to a frequency
in Hertz (so that "69" converts to "440"). Microtonal pitches are possible
\, where "69.5" is a quarter tone higher than 69 (or 50 cents higher
\, so 0.01 = 1 cent)., f 70;
#X text 24 143 The [ftom] object does the reverse. A frequency of zero
Hertz is given a MIDI value of -1500 (strictly speaking \, it's negative
infinity.), f 70;
#X text 24 359 A dBFS scale is possible if you simply add 100 to the
dB input value or subtract 100 from the dB output value (in this case
\, minus infinity dB is clipped to -100 dBFS)., f 70;
#X text 24 406 Finally \, [dbtopow] and [powtodb] convert decibels
to and from power units \, equal to the square of the "RMS" amplitude.
, f 70;
#X text 24 180 The [dbtorms] object converts from dB to linear ("RMS")
amplitude. Decibels in Pd are basically dBFS with an offset of 100!
Hence \, the typical range is arbitrarily set from 0 to 100 dB (where
100 dB corresponds to an "RMS" of 1). When converted to linear amplitude
\, negative dB values are clipped to zero "RMS". Zero dB \, which should
correspond to 1e-05 in linear "RMS" \, is rounded down to zero instead.
, f 70;
